{
  "doc_id": "1196",
  "text": "To some extent, the trade unionists in this study were working in a similar way to the IT actors in [CITATION_1] study, who continuously shaped and re-shaped change programmes based upon their own insights. [CITATION_2] noted similar translation processes to those used in this case, in terms of alignment, enrolment and congealment; however, they also noted the role of hegemonic power processes in terms of others within the organization evaluating how the IT change might impact upon their own power position. The translators in their study had sufficient access to power and resources to make the translations happen and this is characteristic of other studies in the field. Those who lead the cause in other translation studies are often powerful actors: for example, the directors and managers in [CITATION_3] study, the managing directors, ministers and government in [CITATION_4] account, and the industrial and firm-level actors in [CITATION_5] study.",
